1
00:00:06,089 --> 00:00:07,800
What if I say
something dumb?

2
00:00:07,800 --> 00:00:09,635
Something that makes
him uncomfortable?

3
00:00:09,635 --> 00:00:10,761
Like what?

4
00:00:10,761 --> 00:00:13,054
Like, "How's
your new leg?"

5
00:00:13,054 --> 00:00:15,766
I think he's probably
expecting a few questions.

6
00:00:15,766 --> 00:00:17,142
I just don't want
to say the wrong thing.

7
00:00:17,142 --> 00:00:18,727
You'll be fine.

8
00:00:18,727 --> 00:00:20,562
But maybe I shouldn't
be there when he arrives.

9
00:00:20,562 --> 00:00:21,939
Why?

10
00:00:21,939 --> 00:00:23,607
Well, when he was
in the hospital

11
00:00:23,607 --> 00:00:25,275
he didn't answer
any of my letters.

12
00:00:25,275 --> 00:00:27,736
That's okay.
I'm only his stepmother.

13
00:00:27,736 --> 00:00:30,823
But he's going through
something so personal

14
00:00:30,823 --> 00:00:32,783
maybe he only wants
his real family around.

15
00:00:32,783 --> 00:00:34,618
You<i> are</i> real family.

16
00:00:34,618 --> 00:00:36,203
That's right

17
00:00:36,203 --> 00:00:38,747
and you should
both just relax.

18
00:00:38,747 --> 00:00:40,207
Yes, Nog has lost a leg

19
00:00:40,207 --> 00:00:41,834
and that's a
traumatic experience

20
00:00:41,834 --> 00:00:43,669
but nothing you do
or say is going

21
00:00:43,669 --> 00:00:45,671
to be worse than what
he's already gone through.

22
00:00:45,671 --> 00:00:48,549
Just be happy to see him
and tell him you love him.

23
00:00:48,549 --> 00:00:50,049
For today, that'll be enough.

24
00:00:50,049 --> 00:00:51,635
They've docked.

25
00:00:59,309 --> 00:01:01,061
Welcome aboard.
Thanks.

26
00:01:01,061 --> 00:01:02,437
BLONDE WOMAN:
Aha, there you are.

27
00:01:02,437 --> 00:01:03,480
Hi.

28
00:01:03,480 --> 00:01:04,356
How are you?

29
00:01:04,356 --> 00:01:05,482
I'm fine.

30
00:01:12,907 --> 00:01:15,701
Colonel, are you sure

31
00:01:15,701 --> 00:01:17,077
this is the
right transport?

32
00:01:17,077 --> 00:01:18,537
I checked the passenger list
this morning.

33
00:01:18,537 --> 00:01:19,747
He definitely boarded it.

34
00:01:19,747 --> 00:01:21,582
LEETA:
Here he comes.

35
00:01:29,715 --> 00:01:31,926
(<i> applause</i> )

36
00:01:39,934 --> 00:01:41,685
Welcome back, Nog.

37
00:01:41,685 --> 00:01:44,063
ROM: It's good
to have you home.
LEETA: Welcome home, Nog.

38
00:01:44,063 --> 00:01:45,981
Thank you. Thank you.
It's good to be back.

39
00:01:45,981 --> 00:01:47,399
My orders, Captain.

40
00:01:48,901 --> 00:01:50,903
"Medical leave"?
How could that be?

41
00:01:50,903 --> 00:01:52,446
O'BRIEN:
Sounds like an excuse
to loaf around

42
00:01:52,446 --> 00:01:53,572
while the rest
of us work.

43
00:01:53,572 --> 00:01:55,032
Hard work and
plenty of it--

44
00:01:55,032 --> 00:01:57,117
that's what
I prescribe.

45
00:01:57,117 --> 00:01:58,869
Captain, maybe he
forged those orders.

46
00:01:58,869 --> 00:02:00,579
SISKO:
I'm afraid
they're genuine.

47
00:02:00,579 --> 00:02:03,248
"Ensign Nog has no duties
until further notice."

48
00:02:03,248 --> 00:02:07,086
Except... to attend
a "Welcome Home"

49
00:02:07,086 --> 00:02:08,545
party in the Wardroom.

50
00:02:12,257 --> 00:02:16,177
If it's all the same
to you, sir,
I'm rather tired.

51
00:02:16,177 --> 00:02:19,431
I'd rather just go
to my quarters.
Is that all right?

52
00:02:19,431 --> 00:02:22,726
Absolutely. We can
celebrate once you've
settled in.

53
00:02:22,726 --> 00:02:24,269
Great.

54
00:02:24,269 --> 00:02:25,813
I can carry your bag.

55
00:02:25,813 --> 00:02:27,106
I've got it.

56
00:02:28,690 --> 00:02:30,567
Well, if you'll all excuse me.

57
00:04:46,912 --> 00:04:49,372
...and Julian and Miles
have become even more obsessed

58
00:04:49,372 --> 00:04:52,000
with their Alamo program,
if you can believe it.

59
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:53,418
I half expect Miles

60
00:04:53,418 --> 00:04:55,879
to start wearing
a coonskin cap to work.

61
00:04:58,257 --> 00:05:00,968
You see, Davy Crockett
wore this cap...

62
00:05:00,968 --> 00:05:03,053
made of raccoon skin and...

63
00:05:03,053 --> 00:05:04,471
I know the program.

64
00:05:04,471 --> 00:05:06,306
Oh.

65
00:05:06,306 --> 00:05:09,559
Well, I think
we've covered

66
00:05:09,559 --> 00:05:10,769
just about everything
you missed

67
00:05:10,769 --> 00:05:12,062
while you were away.

68
00:05:12,062 --> 00:05:14,355
Is there anything
you want to talk about?

69
00:05:15,607 --> 00:05:17,234
Not particularly.

70
00:05:20,737 --> 00:05:23,073
(<i> sighs</i> )

71
00:05:23,073 --> 00:05:24,449
Here it comes.

72
00:05:24,449 --> 00:05:25,784
What?

73
00:05:25,784 --> 00:05:27,661
The "cane problem."

74
00:05:27,661 --> 00:05:29,663
You're about
to ask me why

75
00:05:29,663 --> 00:05:31,456
I need to walk
with a cane

76
00:05:31,456 --> 00:05:33,374
since Dr. Benbasset told you

77
00:05:33,374 --> 00:05:36,503
my biosynthetic leg works
perfectly.

78
00:05:36,503 --> 00:05:41,091
He also told you the problem's
all in my head, that I'm crazy.

79
00:05:41,091 --> 00:05:42,383
He didn't say that.

80
00:05:42,383 --> 00:05:44,385
That's what he thinks.

81
00:05:44,385 --> 00:05:46,221
Forget what he thinks.

82
00:05:46,221 --> 00:05:47,806
What do you think?

83
00:05:47,806 --> 00:05:49,516
Why do you need the cane?

84
00:05:49,516 --> 00:05:51,601
My leg hurts.

85
00:05:51,601 --> 00:05:53,812
And if I put
my full weight on it

86
00:05:53,812 --> 00:05:56,481
it hurts more, so I have to limp

87
00:05:56,481 --> 00:05:58,984
and that means I need
to walk with a cane.

88
00:05:58,984 --> 00:06:01,069
That sounds reasonable to me.

89
00:06:02,070 --> 00:06:03,322
Good.

90
00:06:05,699 --> 00:06:08,327
(<i> sighs heavily</i> )

91
00:06:08,327 --> 00:06:11,079
Look, can I be
perfectly honest with you?

92
00:06:12,622 --> 00:06:14,624
I've spent the last three weeks

93
00:06:14,624 --> 00:06:16,626
talking about my feelings

94
00:06:16,626 --> 00:06:19,129
with the counselors
on Starbase 235

95
00:06:19,129 --> 00:06:22,049
and to tell you the truth,
I'm a little sick of it.

96
00:06:23,466 --> 00:06:26,136
I just want to be left alone
for a while.

97
00:06:26,136 --> 00:06:27,804
I understand.

98
00:06:29,597 --> 00:06:31,766
I think we've
done enough for today.

99
00:06:33,392 --> 00:06:34,936
I'll see you tomorrow.

100
00:06:48,491 --> 00:06:50,952
Computer, what time is it?

101
00:06:50,952 --> 00:06:53,496
COMPUTER:
The time is 0932 hours.

102
00:06:53,496 --> 00:06:55,040
NOG:
(<i> sighs</i> )

103
00:07:14,559 --> 00:07:16,811
(<i> soft piano music plays</i> )

104
00:07:26,905 --> 00:07:32,244
VIC FONTAINE:
♪ I'll be seeing you ♪

105
00:07:32,244 --> 00:07:38,041
♪ In all
the old familiar places ♪

106
00:07:38,041 --> 00:07:43,004
♪ That this heart
of mine embraces... ♪

107
00:07:43,004 --> 00:07:46,049
Jake says he's been sleeping
over 18 hours a day

108
00:07:46,049 --> 00:07:47,384
and Julian says he's missed

109
00:07:47,384 --> 00:07:49,719
his last two physical
therapy appointments.

110
00:07:49,719 --> 00:07:52,513
And his counseling sessions
have been going nowhere.

111
00:07:52,513 --> 00:07:54,515
In his words, he's
"sick of talking

112
00:07:54,515 --> 00:07:55,767
about his feelings."

113
00:07:55,767 --> 00:07:57,978
I can't say I blame him.

114
00:07:57,978 --> 00:07:59,980
He's been under constant
psychiatric care

115
00:07:59,980 --> 00:08:01,356
for almost two months now.

116
00:08:01,356 --> 00:08:02,565
What should we do?

117
00:08:02,565 --> 00:08:05,193
I'm not sure.

118
00:08:05,193 --> 00:08:06,903
For now, I think
our best bet

119
00:08:06,903 --> 00:08:08,529
is to simply
watch and wait.

120
00:08:08,529 --> 00:08:09,656
Not my first choice.

121
00:08:09,656 --> 00:08:10,991
I know

122
00:08:10,991 --> 00:08:12,242
but sometimes a patient

123
00:08:12,242 --> 00:08:14,202
can help guide
his own treatment.

124
00:08:14,202 --> 00:08:16,788
Let's see what
Nog does next.

125
00:08:22,252 --> 00:08:28,008
♪ ...but I'll be seeing you. ♪

126
00:08:32,887 --> 00:08:35,265
(<i> song ends</i> )

127
00:08:42,605 --> 00:08:43,606
(<i> song begins</i> )

128
00:08:43,606 --> 00:08:45,608
♪ I'll be seeing you ♪

129
00:08:45,608 --> 00:08:49,321
JAKE:
(<i> sighs</i> )

130
00:08:49,321 --> 00:08:52,032
♪ In all the old ♪

131
00:08:52,032 --> 00:08:53,783
♪ Familiar places... ♪

132
00:08:53,783 --> 00:08:56,286
Nog, I am trying
to be understanding

133
00:08:56,286 --> 00:08:57,912
and I want to be
your friend

134
00:08:57,912 --> 00:08:59,873
but enough is enough!

135
00:08:59,873 --> 00:09:03,084
You've been playing that same
stupid song for three days.

136
00:09:03,084 --> 00:09:04,794
I-I can't take
it anymore.

137
00:09:07,047 --> 00:09:08,923
Aren't you going
to say anything?

138
00:09:08,923 --> 00:09:11,634
You've barely said three words
to me since you came home.

139
00:09:11,634 --> 00:09:14,262
Maybe I don't have
anything to say.

140
00:09:14,262 --> 00:09:16,764
(<i> sighs</i> ) I'm trying
to help you here, Nog

141
00:09:16,764 --> 00:09:18,266
but you're not
making it easy.

142
00:09:18,266 --> 00:09:21,895
You want to help me? Fine.

143
00:09:21,895 --> 00:09:24,105
Leave me alone.

144
00:09:24,105 --> 00:09:26,607
All right. Okay.

145
00:09:26,607 --> 00:09:28,985
But if you want to hear
that song again

146
00:09:28,985 --> 00:09:30,904
go rent a holosuite!

147
00:10:17,325 --> 00:10:18,826
(<i> screaming</i> )

148
00:10:23,164 --> 00:10:24,999
(<i> yells</i> )

149
00:10:24,999 --> 00:10:27,586
(<i> high-pitched scream</i> )

150
00:10:45,895 --> 00:10:47,314
COMPUTER:
Program is running.

151
00:10:47,314 --> 00:10:48,940
You may enter when ready.

152
00:10:56,781 --> 00:10:59,075
Hi, there, pally.

153
00:10:59,075 --> 00:11:00,494
Gee, it's good
to see you.

154
00:11:00,494 --> 00:11:01,995
Vic Fontaine.

155
00:11:01,995 --> 00:11:04,456
I know. I'm Nog.

156
00:11:04,456 --> 00:11:05,748
You're Rom's
kid, right?

157
00:11:05,748 --> 00:11:06,707
Right.

158
00:11:06,707 --> 00:11:08,084
He's really
proud of you.

159
00:11:08,084 --> 00:11:09,252
He's always
in here bragging

160
00:11:09,252 --> 00:11:10,337
about his son,
the soldier boy.

161
00:11:10,337 --> 00:11:11,671
Yeah.

162
00:11:11,671 --> 00:11:13,173
What can I
do for you?

163
00:11:13,173 --> 00:11:15,716
I want to hear
"I'll Be Seeing You."

164
00:11:15,716 --> 00:11:18,052
Sure thing, kiddo.
Any other requests?

165
00:11:18,052 --> 00:11:22,890
No. Just...
"I'll Be Seeing You."

166
00:11:22,890 --> 00:11:24,518
Sounds like a special tune.

167
00:11:25,477 --> 00:11:27,228
It is.

168
00:11:27,228 --> 00:11:30,649
It helped me once
when I was... unhappy.

169
00:11:30,649 --> 00:11:32,942
What more can you ask
from a song?

170
00:11:34,444 --> 00:11:37,572
"I'll Be Seeing You."
From the top.

171
00:11:37,572 --> 00:11:40,283
(<i> piano plays</i>
<i>slow introduction</i> )

172
00:11:49,250 --> 00:11:54,381
♪ I'll be seeing you ♪

173
00:11:54,381 --> 00:11:59,093
♪ In all the old,
familiar places... ♪

174
00:11:59,093 --> 00:12:00,470
Doctor...

175
00:12:00,470 --> 00:12:02,472
♪ That this heart
of mine embraces... ♪

176
00:12:02,472 --> 00:12:03,890
Yes?

177
00:12:03,890 --> 00:12:05,850
What is that?

178
00:12:05,850 --> 00:12:08,520
It's a song that I had
Vic Fontaine record for me.

179
00:12:08,520 --> 00:12:10,355
Vic...

180
00:12:10,355 --> 00:12:12,899
Yes. He's a character
in a holosuite program of mine.

181
00:12:12,899 --> 00:12:15,694
I thought it might take
our minds off our troubles.

182
00:12:15,694 --> 00:12:17,278
Is it bothering you?

183
00:12:17,278 --> 00:12:22,701
No. It's kind of nice.

184
00:12:22,701 --> 00:12:25,453
♪ ...the chestnut tree ♪

185
00:12:25,453 --> 00:12:29,332
♪ The wishing well ♪

186
00:12:29,332 --> 00:12:33,253
♪ I'll be seeing you ♪

187
00:12:33,253 --> 00:12:38,216
♪ In every lovely summer's day ♪

188
00:12:38,216 --> 00:12:40,051
♪ In everything ♪

189
00:12:40,051 --> 00:12:43,012
♪ That's bright and gay ♪

190
00:12:43,012 --> 00:12:46,140
♪ I'll always think of you... ♪

191
00:12:46,140 --> 00:12:49,977
(<i> with upbeat tempo</i> ):
♪ ...I'll find you
in the morning sun ♪

192
00:12:49,977 --> 00:12:52,855
♪ And when the night is new ♪

193
00:12:52,855 --> 00:12:55,149
♪ I'll be looking at the moon ♪

194
00:12:55,149 --> 00:12:57,985
♪ But I'll be seeing you ♪

195
00:12:59,987 --> 00:13:03,991
♪ I'll find you
in the morning sun ♪

196
00:13:03,991 --> 00:13:07,412
♪ And when the night is new ♪

197
00:13:07,412 --> 00:13:10,123
♪ I'll be looking at the moon ♪

198
00:13:10,123 --> 00:13:14,210
♪ But I'll be seeing you. ♪

199
00:13:16,837 --> 00:13:17,796
Thank you.

200
00:13:17,796 --> 00:13:19,006
Take five, fellas.

201
00:13:19,006 --> 00:13:20,550
Okay, kid, I know

202
00:13:20,550 --> 00:13:22,469
15 different arrangements
of that song.

203
00:13:22,469 --> 00:13:23,844
You've heard them all.

204
00:13:23,844 --> 00:13:24,887
Now which one's
your favorite?

205
00:13:26,055 --> 00:13:27,974
The first.

206
00:13:27,974 --> 00:13:30,769
(<i> chuckles</i> ):
Somehow, I knew you
were going to say that.

207
00:13:30,769 --> 00:13:33,688
So let me guess-- Julian
played it for you, right?

208
00:13:33,688 --> 00:13:35,231
Right.

209
00:13:35,231 --> 00:13:36,441
If I had him
as a publicist

210
00:13:36,441 --> 00:13:37,858
I'd be bigger
than Elvis.

211
00:13:37,858 --> 00:13:39,152
Who?

212
00:13:39,152 --> 00:13:41,362
Never mind.

213
00:13:41,362 --> 00:13:43,531
So... how's the new leg?

214
00:13:45,866 --> 00:13:47,160
You know about that?

215
00:13:47,160 --> 00:13:48,578
People talk.

216
00:13:53,333 --> 00:13:55,627
If you really want to know...

217
00:13:55,627 --> 00:13:57,587
it hurts.

218
00:13:57,587 --> 00:13:59,964
Can they give you
something for that?

219
00:13:59,964 --> 00:14:03,593
No. They say
it's all in my head.

220
00:14:05,261 --> 00:14:07,054
"According to my tricorder

221
00:14:07,054 --> 00:14:10,266
"the pain receptors in your leg
aren't being stimulated, Nog.

222
00:14:10,266 --> 00:14:12,519
You must be imagining it."

223
00:14:12,519 --> 00:14:15,355
But I don't care what they say.

224
00:14:15,355 --> 00:14:17,440
It hurts all the time.

225
00:14:20,067 --> 00:14:21,319
I believe you.

226
00:14:21,319 --> 00:14:23,321
(<i> sighs</i> )

227
00:14:23,321 --> 00:14:24,531
You're the only one.

228
00:14:27,492 --> 00:14:28,827
So what else can I do for you?

229
00:14:28,827 --> 00:14:29,869
Sing it again?

230
00:14:29,869 --> 00:14:31,912
No.

231
00:14:31,912 --> 00:14:33,080
Good.

232
00:14:33,080 --> 00:14:34,624
To tell you the truth

233
00:14:34,624 --> 00:14:36,917
I was starting to get
a little sick of it myself.

234
00:14:36,917 --> 00:14:38,378
How about something else?

235
00:14:38,378 --> 00:14:40,463
No.

236
00:14:40,463 --> 00:14:43,424
I just want to go to bed.

237
00:14:44,718 --> 00:14:47,345
Okay, kid.
Catch you later, huh?

238
00:14:47,345 --> 00:14:48,429
Yeah.

239
00:14:53,560 --> 00:14:54,769
Something wrong?

240
00:14:55,936 --> 00:14:59,106
I don't want to go
back to my quarters.

241
00:14:59,106 --> 00:15:00,983
(<i> sighs</i> )

242
00:15:00,983 --> 00:15:03,486
Actually, I don't want
to go back to my life.

243
00:15:08,324 --> 00:15:09,950
Vic...

244
00:15:11,619 --> 00:15:13,079
where do you live?

245
00:15:14,247 --> 00:15:15,956
In the program, I mean.

246
00:15:15,956 --> 00:15:17,458
Do you have a house or...

247
00:15:17,458 --> 00:15:19,085
I have a suite
here in the hotel.

248
00:15:20,294 --> 00:15:21,796
Do you have an extra room?

249
00:15:21,796 --> 00:15:24,382
Sure. You want to stay
with me tonight?

250
00:15:24,382 --> 00:15:26,801
Maybe more than
just tonight.

251
00:15:26,801 --> 00:15:29,262
Officially, I'm
on medical leave

252
00:15:29,262 --> 00:15:30,638
and according
to regulations

253
00:15:30,638 --> 00:15:32,766
I can choose my
rehabilitation facility.

254
00:15:32,766 --> 00:15:35,810
You want to choose a holosuite
program for your rehab?

255
00:15:35,810 --> 00:15:36,977
Why not?

256
00:15:38,813 --> 00:15:41,315
Okay, kid... if that's
the way you want it

257
00:15:41,315 --> 00:15:42,859
from now on,
you're staying with me.

258
00:15:42,859 --> 00:15:44,277
Great.

259
00:15:45,361 --> 00:15:46,404
Crazy.

260
00:15:51,576 --> 00:15:53,035
My son is insane.

261
00:15:53,035 --> 00:15:54,203
EZRI:
Rom...

262
00:15:54,203 --> 00:15:55,538
He's a one-legged crazy man!

263
00:15:55,538 --> 00:15:56,790
He is not crazy.

264
00:15:56,790 --> 00:15:58,583
But he<i> is</i> living
in a holosuite.

265
00:16:00,585 --> 00:16:04,171
At first, it struck me
as a little... peculiar

266
00:16:04,171 --> 00:16:06,591
but after I thought it over,
I began to think

267
00:16:06,591 --> 00:16:08,676
that this might be
a good sign after all.

268
00:16:08,676 --> 00:16:10,470
How can hiding
in one of Julian's

269
00:16:10,470 --> 00:16:12,138
adolescent programs
be a good sign?

270
00:16:12,138 --> 00:16:13,723
Hey...
It could be worse.

271
00:16:13,723 --> 00:16:15,558
He could be hiding
in the Alamo program.

272
00:16:15,558 --> 00:16:16,810
LEETA:
Or that ridiculous

273
00:16:16,810 --> 00:16:18,394
secret agent program.

274
00:16:18,394 --> 00:16:19,562
Hey...

275
00:16:19,562 --> 00:16:20,855
Or that stupid Viking program.

276
00:16:20,855 --> 00:16:22,857
Hey!
All right.

277
00:16:22,857 --> 00:16:26,152
Are you sure this is
in Nog's best interest?

278
00:16:26,152 --> 00:16:27,904
No, I'm not sure

279
00:16:27,904 --> 00:16:31,532
but I think Nog might be
subconsciously trying

280
00:16:31,532 --> 00:16:33,785
to seek out his own
form of therapy.

281
00:16:33,785 --> 00:16:37,246
I'm sorry, but moving
into a holosuite isn't my idea

282
00:16:37,246 --> 00:16:38,331
of therapy.

283
00:16:38,331 --> 00:16:40,249
Okay. It sounds
a little odd.

284
00:16:40,249 --> 00:16:41,375
QUARK:
It sounds

285
00:16:41,375 --> 00:16:42,961
ridiculous.
BASHIR:
Not really.

286
00:16:42,961 --> 00:16:46,005
I'm inclined to agree
with Ezri on this one.

287
00:16:46,005 --> 00:16:49,258
The mind has a strong natural
instinct for survival.

288
00:16:49,258 --> 00:16:51,469
Now, for whatever reason,
Nog's mind has chosen

289
00:16:51,469 --> 00:16:54,096
to take shelter in the
world of Vic Fontaine.

290
00:16:54,096 --> 00:16:56,766
I think we should wait
and see how this plays out.

291
00:16:56,766 --> 00:16:59,853
Then someone should talk
to Vic, make him aware

292
00:16:59,853 --> 00:17:02,897
of Nog's emotional
and physical condition.

293
00:17:02,897 --> 00:17:04,190
I'll do it.

294
00:17:04,190 --> 00:17:05,525
And who's going
to be paying

295
00:17:05,525 --> 00:17:06,776
for all this
holosuite time?

296
00:17:10,780 --> 00:17:12,573
I guess I am.

297
00:17:12,573 --> 00:17:15,075
And it's<i> very</i> generous of you.

298
00:17:17,620 --> 00:17:18,997
Keep me informed.

299
00:17:25,336 --> 00:17:27,338
I get it. He's got
some healing to do.

300
00:17:27,338 --> 00:17:29,215
I could spot that
the moment he walked in here.

301
00:17:29,215 --> 00:17:31,467
Great. Do you have
any questions?

302
00:17:31,467 --> 00:17:32,886
You sure he doesn't
need the cane?

303
00:17:32,886 --> 00:17:34,136
Because he's
pretty sure he does.

304
00:17:34,136 --> 00:17:35,889
I'm positive.

305
00:17:35,889 --> 00:17:37,640
It's a psychological need,
not a physical one.

306
00:17:37,640 --> 00:17:38,933
Well, then I have
some ideas

307
00:17:38,933 --> 00:17:40,351
on how to wean him
off the stick.

308
00:17:40,351 --> 00:17:43,021
Okay, but don't push it.

309
00:17:43,021 --> 00:17:44,564
Do I seem pushy to you?

310
00:17:44,564 --> 00:17:47,984
No. Well, you know
how to reach me

311
00:17:47,984 --> 00:17:49,068
if you have
any problems.

312
00:17:49,068 --> 00:17:50,653
I got your number.

313
00:17:57,702 --> 00:17:59,913
So you're Jack Wilson.

314
00:17:59,913 --> 00:18:01,748
What's that mean
to<i> you,</i> Shane?

315
00:18:03,041 --> 00:18:04,124
Hey, kid.

316
00:18:04,124 --> 00:18:05,084
Hey, Vic.

317
00:18:05,084 --> 00:18:06,335
Have you seen this movie?

318
00:18:06,335 --> 00:18:07,503
Oh, yeah.

319
00:18:07,503 --> 00:18:10,381
JACK:
What have you heard, Shane?

320
00:18:10,381 --> 00:18:12,675
SHANE:
I've heard that you're a lowdown

321
00:18:12,675 --> 00:18:14,510
Yankee liar.

322
00:18:22,643 --> 00:18:23,937
Shane, look out!

323
00:18:26,856 --> 00:18:28,399
From these books,
I can't tell

324
00:18:28,399 --> 00:18:29,734
if I'm as rich
as Rockefeller

325
00:18:29,734 --> 00:18:31,069
or poor as a church mouse.

326
00:18:31,069 --> 00:18:32,445
It's not real money, Vic.

327
00:18:32,445 --> 00:18:33,487
Don't worry about it.

328
00:18:33,487 --> 00:18:35,531
Hey, it's real to me, kid.

329
00:18:35,531 --> 00:18:37,951
Well, I can have the computer
put some money in your account.

330
00:18:37,951 --> 00:18:39,035
No, thanks.

331
00:18:39,035 --> 00:18:40,745
I'll figure it out.

332
00:18:43,289 --> 00:18:44,624
I got to be going on.

333
00:18:46,375 --> 00:18:48,294
Why, Shane?

334
00:18:48,294 --> 00:18:51,005
Didn't he just get shot
a minute ago?

335
00:18:51,005 --> 00:18:53,382
Yeah. He took one
in the arm.

336
00:18:53,382 --> 00:18:54,801
He's not bleeding.

337
00:18:54,801 --> 00:18:56,260
He's not even in pain.

338
00:18:56,260 --> 00:18:58,096
Noggles, take it easy.
It's only a movie.

339
00:18:59,764 --> 00:19:03,768
(<i> echoing</i> ):
Shane!

340
00:19:03,768 --> 00:19:06,437
Come back!

341
00:19:20,952 --> 00:19:22,870
I like
<i>The Searchers</i> better.

342
00:19:22,870 --> 00:19:24,330
Yeah. Who doesn't?

343
00:19:24,330 --> 00:19:25,498
Son of a gun.

344
00:19:25,498 --> 00:19:27,000
I got to get ready
for the show.

345
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:29,293
Show? I thought
we were hanging in.

346
00:19:29,293 --> 00:19:30,962
No, "hanging out."

347
00:19:30,962 --> 00:19:32,839
And we are, except
I have a gig to do.

348
00:19:32,839 --> 00:19:33,798
Cancel it.

349
00:19:33,798 --> 00:19:34,882
I can't do that.

350
00:19:34,882 --> 00:19:35,883
Why not?

351
00:19:35,883 --> 00:19:37,010
It would be
unprofessional.

352
00:19:37,010 --> 00:19:38,594
Besides, performing is my life.

353
00:19:38,594 --> 00:19:39,762
It's what I do.

354
00:19:39,762 --> 00:19:41,388
I got to get out there
and swing.

355
00:19:41,388 --> 00:19:43,182
Otherwise, I'm just
another Clyde in a tux.

356
00:19:44,391 --> 00:19:46,060
You coming
to the show?

357
00:19:47,728 --> 00:19:49,105
Sure.

358
00:19:49,105 --> 00:19:50,523
Good.

359
00:19:52,483 --> 00:19:54,527
Then, may I suggest you, uh...

360
00:19:54,527 --> 00:19:57,237
carry something
with a little more...

361
00:19:57,237 --> 00:19:58,156
style?

362
00:19:58,156 --> 00:20:01,659
Now,<i> this</i> is a cane.

363
00:20:01,659 --> 00:20:02,994
It's a replica

364
00:20:02,994 --> 00:20:04,996
of the one Errol Flynn
used to have...

365
00:20:04,996 --> 00:20:06,831
only his was a little taller.

366
00:20:06,831 --> 00:20:09,167
It's beautiful.

367
00:20:09,167 --> 00:20:11,460
It reminds me
of the Grand Nagus' staff.

368
00:20:11,460 --> 00:20:12,879
It has
a little secret.

369
00:20:12,879 --> 00:20:14,547
Push that button
at the back of the head.

370
00:20:17,884 --> 00:20:19,760
(<i> laughing</i> )

371
00:20:19,760 --> 00:20:21,387
Great! But what's it for?

372
00:20:21,387 --> 00:20:23,723
You never know when a lady's
gonna need a light.

373
00:20:23,723 --> 00:20:24,765
Now, be careful
with that stick.

374
00:20:24,765 --> 00:20:26,559
It's fragile.

375
00:20:26,559 --> 00:20:28,268
It might not hold
your whole weight.

376
00:20:28,268 --> 00:20:31,230
Actually, I don't need
to put my whole weight on it.

377
00:20:32,190 --> 00:20:33,482
Good.

378
00:20:33,482 --> 00:20:34,358
Now, let's get dressed.

379
00:20:34,358 --> 00:20:35,526
Tuxedos?

380
00:20:35,526 --> 00:20:37,737
You're catching on.

381
00:20:37,737 --> 00:20:38,863
(<i> chuckling</i> )

382
00:20:40,823 --> 00:20:43,409
♪ I've got a song that I sing ♪

383
00:20:43,409 --> 00:20:45,870
♪ I can make the rain go ♪

384
00:20:45,870 --> 00:20:49,248
♪ Any time I move my finger ♪

385
00:20:49,248 --> 00:20:50,583
♪ Lucky me ♪

386
00:20:50,583 --> 00:20:53,586
♪ Can't you see I'm in love? ♪

387
00:20:54,837 --> 00:20:57,131
♪ Life is a beautiful thing ♪

388
00:20:58,966 --> 00:21:01,468
♪ As long as
I hold that string ♪

389
00:21:01,468 --> 00:21:05,765
♪ I'd be a silly so-and-so ♪

390
00:21:05,765 --> 00:21:08,101
♪ If I should ever let it go ♪

391
00:21:10,061 --> 00:21:13,022
♪ I've got the world
on a string ♪

392
00:21:13,022 --> 00:21:15,482
♪ Sittin' on a rainbow ♪

393
00:21:15,482 --> 00:21:18,444
♪ Got the string
around my finger ♪

394
00:21:18,444 --> 00:21:20,571
♪ What a world... ♪

395
00:21:20,571 --> 00:21:22,448
JAKE:
Hey, have you seen Nog?

396
00:21:22,448 --> 00:21:24,491
I think I see him sitting
right over there.

397
00:21:24,491 --> 00:21:25,826
JAKE:
All right, thanks.

398
00:21:25,826 --> 00:21:28,037
♪ Life is a beautiful thing ♪

399
00:21:28,037 --> 00:21:31,082
♪ As long as I hold
that string... ♪

400
00:21:31,082 --> 00:21:32,583
Hi, there.

401
00:21:32,583 --> 00:21:34,501
Nog, let me
introduce you to...

402
00:21:34,501 --> 00:21:36,129
MAN:
Down in front.

403
00:21:36,129 --> 00:21:37,504
Sorry.

404
00:21:39,506 --> 00:21:41,717
Nog, this is Kesha.

405
00:21:41,717 --> 00:21:43,719
Kesha, Nog.

406
00:21:43,719 --> 00:21:44,678
Nice to meet you.

407
00:21:44,678 --> 00:21:46,346
Welcome
to Las Vegas.

408
00:21:46,346 --> 00:21:47,598
Thanks.

409
00:21:47,598 --> 00:21:48,808
♪ ...around my finger ♪

410
00:21:48,808 --> 00:21:51,477
♪ What a world, what a life ♪

411
00:21:52,895 --> 00:21:55,273
♪ What a world, what a life ♪

412
00:21:56,523 --> 00:21:59,068
♪ What a world, what a life ♪

413
00:21:59,068 --> 00:22:04,031
♪ I'm in love. ♪

414
00:22:06,867 --> 00:22:07,952
Thank you,
thank you.

415
00:22:07,952 --> 00:22:09,245
You're too kind.

416
00:22:09,245 --> 00:22:10,913
I guess that's
the response you get

417
00:22:10,913 --> 00:22:11,872
when you pack the house
with relatives.

418
00:22:11,872 --> 00:22:14,500
(<i> laughter</i> )

419
00:22:14,500 --> 00:22:17,461
(<i> band starts intro</i>
<i>to "Just In Time"</i> )

420
00:22:20,006 --> 00:22:21,966
So, uh, what
have you been doing?

421
00:22:21,966 --> 00:22:23,801
Hanging out.

422
00:22:23,801 --> 00:22:24,844
Out of what?

423
00:22:24,844 --> 00:22:26,971
It's an expression.

424
00:22:26,971 --> 00:22:29,723
There's a lot of
old Earth slang in this program.

425
00:22:29,723 --> 00:22:31,058
Right, daddy-o?

426
00:22:31,058 --> 00:22:32,726
Right.

427
00:22:34,854 --> 00:22:37,064
Why don't I get us
some drinks, huh?

428
00:22:37,064 --> 00:22:38,149
Kesha,
what'll you have?

429
00:22:38,149 --> 00:22:39,192
A Makara fizz.

430
00:22:39,192 --> 00:22:40,651
They don't serve that here.

431
00:22:40,651 --> 00:22:42,862
Oh. Well, what
are you having?

432
00:22:42,862 --> 00:22:45,239
A martini. Two olives.

433
00:22:45,239 --> 00:22:46,699
I'll have the same.

434
00:22:46,699 --> 00:22:48,201
Okay. I'll be right back.

435
00:22:48,201 --> 00:22:49,785
♪ ...Now you're here ♪

436
00:22:49,785 --> 00:22:54,540
♪ And now I know
just where I'm going... ♪

437
00:22:54,540 --> 00:22:55,916
Jake says you're going to be

438
00:22:55,916 --> 00:22:57,751
the first Ferengi Captain
in Starfleet.

439
00:22:57,751 --> 00:22:59,545
We'll see.

440
00:22:59,545 --> 00:23:01,922
He also says
you're quite a hero.

441
00:23:01,922 --> 00:23:04,133
I'm not a hero.

442
00:23:04,133 --> 00:23:05,759
Don't be so modest.

443
00:23:05,759 --> 00:23:07,220
Jake's not the only one.

444
00:23:07,220 --> 00:23:08,012
Everyone on the station...

445
00:23:08,012 --> 00:23:09,138
I said

446
00:23:09,138 --> 00:23:10,806
I'm not a hero.

447
00:23:10,806 --> 00:23:12,808
Okay.

448
00:23:15,978 --> 00:23:18,064
♪ ...Now you're here ♪

449
00:23:18,064 --> 00:23:21,359
♪ And now I know
just where I'm going ♪

450
00:23:21,359 --> 00:23:23,194
♪ No more doubts... ♪

451
00:23:23,194 --> 00:23:24,195
Which one?

452
00:23:24,195 --> 00:23:25,529
What?

453
00:23:25,529 --> 00:23:26,822
That's what you're
wondering, right?

454
00:23:26,822 --> 00:23:28,074
Which leg is it?

455
00:23:28,074 --> 00:23:30,284
Uh, no, I wasn't wondering
about that.

456
00:23:30,284 --> 00:23:31,327
About what?

457
00:23:31,327 --> 00:23:33,411
About your... you know...

458
00:23:33,411 --> 00:23:35,331
My new leg?

459
00:23:35,331 --> 00:23:36,665
Can't you say it?

460
00:23:36,665 --> 00:23:38,084
No. Yes.

461
00:23:38,084 --> 00:23:40,711
I mean, I'm not trying
to say anything.

462
00:23:40,711 --> 00:23:42,838
Then maybe you should
just keep quiet.

463
00:23:44,382 --> 00:23:45,883
Okay. Here we go.

464
00:23:45,883 --> 00:23:47,260
Three martinis.

465
00:23:47,260 --> 00:23:48,844
I think
we should leave, Jake.

466
00:23:48,844 --> 00:23:50,263
Sounds like a good idea.

467
00:23:50,263 --> 00:23:51,764
What's going on?

468
00:23:51,764 --> 00:23:52,932
It's all my fault.

469
00:23:52,932 --> 00:23:54,350
I didn't mean to stare.

470
00:23:54,350 --> 00:23:55,393
At what?

471
00:23:55,393 --> 00:23:56,476
What do you think?

472
00:23:58,104 --> 00:23:59,437
Oh.

473
00:23:59,437 --> 00:24:00,689
I'm really sorry

474
00:24:00,689 --> 00:24:02,149
if I made you
uncomfortable, Nog.

475
00:24:02,149 --> 00:24:03,984
Wonderful.
Good-bye.

476
00:24:03,984 --> 00:24:06,070
Hold on. She said
she was sorry.

477
00:24:06,070 --> 00:24:07,154
I heard her.

478
00:24:07,154 --> 00:24:08,197
Now you can go.

479
00:24:09,698 --> 00:24:11,658
Nog, what's wrong with you?

480
00:24:11,658 --> 00:24:14,370
I said get out!

481
00:24:14,370 --> 00:24:15,329
Nog...

482
00:24:15,329 --> 00:24:17,039
Let me put it another way.

483
00:24:18,958 --> 00:24:19,833
(<i> Jake groans</i> )

484
00:24:21,543 --> 00:24:23,212
Hey. Hey, hey, hey.
Break it up.

485
00:24:24,422 --> 00:24:25,298
You all right?

486
00:24:25,298 --> 00:24:26,340
Yeah. I'm fine.

487
00:24:26,340 --> 00:24:27,341
And you, take a hike.

488
00:24:27,341 --> 00:24:28,384
What?

489
00:24:28,384 --> 00:24:29,969
You heard me.

490
00:24:29,969 --> 00:24:31,929
You don't come into my club
and start hitting customers.

491
00:24:31,929 --> 00:24:33,639
Now, get out
before I throw you out.

492
00:24:52,325 --> 00:24:53,867
(<i> gunshots on television</i> )

493
00:24:58,705 --> 00:24:59,790
You're still up?

494
00:24:59,790 --> 00:25:01,459
I couldn't sleep.

495
00:25:01,459 --> 00:25:03,377
Do you mind?

496
00:25:06,922 --> 00:25:08,632
What a night.

497
00:25:08,632 --> 00:25:11,093
I'm sorry about
what happened.

498
00:25:11,093 --> 00:25:12,386
Don't apologize
to me.

499
00:25:12,386 --> 00:25:13,720
I'm not the one
you belted.

500
00:25:13,720 --> 00:25:15,513
I'll settle things
with Jake.

501
00:25:15,513 --> 00:25:17,057
<i>And</i> his girl.

502
00:25:17,057 --> 00:25:18,767
Absolutely.

503
00:25:20,060 --> 00:25:22,021
Can I go back
to the club tomorrow night?

504
00:25:22,021 --> 00:25:23,189
I can't
have you

505
00:25:23,189 --> 00:25:24,398
hitting
the customers.

506
00:25:24,398 --> 00:25:25,732
It's not good
for business.

507
00:25:25,732 --> 00:25:28,735
I promise it'll
never happen again.

508
00:25:31,989 --> 00:25:34,033
What got into
you, anyway?

509
00:25:34,033 --> 00:25:35,659
I don't know.

510
00:25:35,659 --> 00:25:39,579
She started calling me
a hero, and...

511
00:25:39,579 --> 00:25:42,249
things just went
downhill from there.

512
00:25:42,249 --> 00:25:44,210
She called you a hero

513
00:25:44,210 --> 00:25:45,794
and for that you slugged
your best friend?

514
00:25:47,213 --> 00:25:49,173
Remind me never to give
you a compliment.

515
00:25:54,178 --> 00:25:56,680
You know, I'm beat.

516
00:25:56,680 --> 00:25:58,932
That's never happened to me.

517
00:25:58,932 --> 00:26:00,600
What?

518
00:26:00,600 --> 00:26:02,102
Being tired.

519
00:26:02,102 --> 00:26:04,522
My program's never run
this long.

520
00:26:04,522 --> 00:26:07,858
Usually people come in,
ask for a song or two--

521
00:26:07,858 --> 00:26:09,527
sometimes a night on the town--

522
00:26:09,527 --> 00:26:11,778
but I never have to put in
a full day.

523
00:26:11,778 --> 00:26:13,864
Maybe you should
go to bed.

524
00:26:13,864 --> 00:26:15,573
I got work to do.

525
00:26:15,573 --> 00:26:18,202
If I don't get
these books in order

526
00:26:18,202 --> 00:26:20,620
Uncle Sam's going
to come down on me

527
00:26:20,620 --> 00:26:22,580
like a ton of bricks.

528
00:26:22,580 --> 00:26:24,083
Sounds like<i> my</i> uncle.

529
00:26:24,083 --> 00:26:26,043
Is there anything I can do?

